    {
        "content": "<p>On the topic of reflexive graphs, I think a reflexive graph as described above amounts to a presheaf/functor from (a category that describes how the edges and vertices relate) to (the category of sets). This should mean that the category of reflexive graphs is really nice - it should inherit limits and colimits from the category of sets, for example. In particular, this means you can take pullbacks in this category, which is important for setting up its category of spans.</p>",
        "id": 495989157,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1737915446
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know how many of the nice properties of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{RGraph}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span></span></span></span> are inherited by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Span}(\\mathsf{RGraph})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Span</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, though. (I'm using <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{RGraph}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span></span></span></span> to refer to the category of reflexive graphs.)</p>",
        "id": 495989160,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1737915452
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They are very different <em>kinds</em> of categories so you shouldn't expect the latter to directly inherit properties from the former.   <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{RGraph}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span></span></span></span> is a category of presheaves, so it's a topos of a particularly simple and nice sort.  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Span}(\\mathsf{RGraph})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Span</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is a bicategory, and a compact closed symmetric monoidal bicategory.   But it's a specially nice one, which Walters and company called a <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/cartesian%20bicategory\">[[cartesian bicategory]]</a>.</p>\n<p>When we water <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Span}(\\mathsf{RGraph})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Span</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> down to a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Span}(\\mathsf{RGraph})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Span</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> by working with isomorphism classes of spans, we get a category that's nothing like a topos.  If I remember correctly, binary products in this category are the same as binary coproducts, which is what we expect from linear algebra:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>≅</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\times B \\cong A + B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>In a topos,  products <em>distribute</em> over coproducts, which is what we expect from set theory:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> A \\times (B + C) \\cong A \\times B + A \\times C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 495993621,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1737919099
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Still, all the exceptionally good properties of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{RGraph}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span></span></span></span> should transmute into <em>different</em> good properties of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Span}(\\mathsf{RGraph})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Span</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.  This is already at work when we consider why <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Span}(\\mathsf{RGraph})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Span</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is a cartesian bicategory (a generalization of a 'category of relations'.)</p>",
        "id": 495994088,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1737919459
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"700428\">@JR Learnstomath</span>: The formalism is very flexible, and I find the notion of system composition present in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Span}(\\mathsf{RGraph})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Span</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">RGraph</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> to be quite convincing. I think a good way to get a feel for this sort of composition is to consider the (admittedly trivial) example of interlocking gears. Section 2.3 of <a href=\"https://kodu.ut.ee/~nester/files/nester-2021-situated-transition-systems.pdf\">one of my papers</a> gives this example, although I think I first encountered it somwhere else --- Maybe in a talk by Nicoletta Sabadini?</p>",
        "id": 497378040,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1738575405
    },
